How to get tramadol for pain?
Tramadol is a medication used to treat moderate to severe pain. It is available in tablet, extended-release (long-acting) capsule, and injectable forms.
Tramadol is a medication used to treat moderate to severe pain. It is available in tablet, extended-release (long-acting) capsule, and injectable forms. Tramadol is a narcotic analgesic, which means it works by blocking pain signals in the brain. It is commonly used to treat pain after surgery and for chronic pain conditions such as arthritis. Tramadol may also be used for other purposes not listed in this medication guide.
You should not take tramadol if you are allergic to it, or if you have:
severe asthma or breathing problems;
a history of drug or alcohol addiction; or
if you are currently using or have recently used sedatives, narcotics, or other pain medications.
Tell your doctor about all of your prescription and nonprescription drug and supplements, including:
aspirin or other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) such as ibuprofen or naproxen;
antihistamines or medications for sleep or cold symptoms;
medications for depression, anxiety, or seizures;
muscle relaxants;
narcotic or opioid medications;
any other medication for pain;
any other prescription or nonprescription medication, vitamins, nutritional supplements, or herbal products;
and for women who are pregnant or breast-feeding.
Do not take tramadol if you are taking a monoamine oxidase inhibitor (MAOI) or have taken an MAO inhibitor within 2 weeks of this medication.
Do not give this medication to anyone else, even if they have the same condition you have. It is against the law.
This medication is usually taken as needed, usually every 4 to 6 hours as needed for pain in 1 or 2 tablets. Do not take more than your doctor has told you to take.
