Metoprolol is a beta-blocker that affects the heart and circulation (blood flow through arteries and veins). Metoprolol is used to treat angina (chest pain) and hypertension (high blood pressure). Metoprolol is also used to lower your risk of death or needing to be hospitalized for heart failure.
Metoprolol may also be used for purposes not listed in this medication guide.
You should not take metoprolol if you have a serious heart problem (heart block, sick sinus syndrome, slow heart rate), severe circulation problems, severe heart failure, or a history of slow heart beats that caused fainting.
You should not take metoprolol if you are allergic to it, or if you have:
- a serious heart problem such as heart block, sick sinus syndrome, or slow heart rate (unless you have a pacemaker);
- severe circulation problems;
- severe heart failure; or
- a history of slow heart beats that caused fainting.
To make sure metoprolol is safe for you, tell your doctor if you have:
- asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), bronchitis, emphysema, or other breathing problems;
- diabetes (metoprolol may make it harder for you to tell when you have low blood sugar);
- circulation problems (such as Raynaud's syndrome);
- a history of allergies;
- liver or kidney disease (or cirrhosis or other condition that causes your liver to not work properly);
- a history of depression;
- pheochromocytoma (tumor of the adrenal gland);
- lupus;
- an electrolyte imbalance (such as low levels of potassium, magnesium, or calcium in your blood); or
- a history of gastrointestinal bleeding.
It is not known whether metoprolol will harm an unborn baby. Tell your doctor if you are pregnant or plan to become pregnant while using this medicine.
