Budesonide is a steroid that prevents the release of substances in the body that cause inflammation. Budesonide inhalations (Pulmicort Flexhaler, Pulmicort Respules, Uceris, Entocort EC) is used to prevent asthma attacks, to treat chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and to treat Crohn’s disease, ulcerative colitis, and microscopic colitis. Budesonide (Entocort EC) is also used to treat a condition in which you cannot stop diarrhea and may also lose weight and become weak (Crohn’s disease).
Budesonide is sometimes used with other medications to treat certain types of cancer (e.g., leukemia). Talk to your doctor about the possible risks of using this drug for your condition.
Budesonide may also be used for purposes not listed in this medication guide.
Important information
You should not use budesonide if you are allergic to it.
To make sure budesonide is safe for you, tell your doctor if you have:
- liver disease (especially cirrhosis);
- a history of tuberculosis;
- a history of cataracts;
- a history of glaucoma or increased pressure in your eye;
- herpes simplex virus of your eyes;
- a parasite infection that requires antibiotics to treat;
- a nerve-muscle disorder, such as myasthenia gravis;
- a food or drug allergy;
- a gastrointestinal disorder such as ulcerative colitis; or
- if you also take lithium (Lithobid).
Budesonide can pass into breast milk and may harm a nursing baby. Tell your doctor if you are breast-feeding a baby.
Steroids can affect growth in children. Talk with your doctor if you think your child is not growing at a normal rate while using this medicine.
How should I take budesonide?
Follow all directions on your prescription label. Your doctor may occasionally change your dose to make sure you get the best results. Do not use this medicine in larger or smaller amounts or for longer than recommended
